01:20.957 --> 01:23.293
MAN: Hiya, Frank.
How are the wife and kids?

01:23.376 --> 01:25.503
You know, for you,
I'm considering treasury bonds

01:25.587 --> 01:28.381
and utility stocks. Smoke?

01:28.465 --> 01:30.550
JARED: <i>In the late '70s,
banking wasn't a job</i>

01:30.633 --> 01:33.136
<i>you went into
to make large sums of money.</i>

01:34.053 --> 01:35.764
<i>It was a fucking snooze.</i>

01:35.847 --> 01:37.640
(CHUCKLES) How about those Mets?

01:37.724 --> 01:40.393
JARED: <i>Filled with losers.
Like selling insurance or</i>

01:40.477 --> 01:41.811
accounting.

01:41.895 --> 01:43.021
And if banking was boring,

01:43.146 --> 01:45.815
then the bond department at the
bank was straight-up comatose.

01:46.649 --> 01:48.026
<i>We all know about bonds.</i>

01:48.109 --> 01:50.229
<i>You give them to your
snot-nosed kid when he turns 15.</i>

01:50.278 --> 01:52.280
Maybe when he's 30
he makes a hundred bucks.

01:52.363 --> 01:53.656
Boring.

01:53.740 --> 01:55.540
That is, until Lewis Ranieri
came on the scene

01:55.617 --> 01:56.659
at Salomon Brothers.

02:02.624 --> 02:04.834
You might not know who he is,
but he changed your life

02:04.918 --> 02:08.630
<i>more than Michael Jordan,
the iPod and YouTube put together.</i>

02:08.713 --> 02:10.465
- (CHUCKLING)
- (MAN LAUGHING)

02:10.548 --> 02:12.300
All right, gentlemen!
Let's get some money in here!

02:12.383 --> 02:14.052
Let's make some money!
What do you say?

02:14.219 --> 02:15.887
(ALL CHEERING)

02:15.970 --> 02:17.806
JARED: <i>You see,
Lewis didn't know it yet,</i>

02:17.889 --> 02:19.808
<i>but he had already
changed banking forever</i>

02:19.891 --> 02:21.100
<i>with one simple idea.</i>

02:21.893 --> 02:26.564
The mortgage-backed security.
Or private-label MBS.

02:27.398 --> 02:29.234
LEWIS: You've got your
average person's mortgage.

02:29.317 --> 02:30.735
Fixed rate, 30 years.

02:30.819 --> 02:34.155
Boring, safe, small payoff, right? But,

02:35.448 --> 02:38.159
when you have thousands
of them all bundled together,

02:38.243 --> 02:41.788
suddenly the yield goes up
but the risk is still small because,

02:41.871 --> 02:42.871
well, they're mortgages!

02:42.914 --> 02:44.332
And who the hell
doesn't pay their mortgage?

02:44.415 --> 02:46.793
What exactly is the credit
rating on this bond?

02:46.876 --> 02:49.712
This bond, gentlemen, is AAA-rated.

02:50.255 --> 02:53.175
This is exactly what the Michigan state
pension fund has been looking for.

02:53.424 --> 02:54.926
I'll buy $20 million.

02:55.009 --> 02:56.177
Oh, come on, live a little.

02:56.302 --> 02:57.929
- $25 million.
- (ALL LAUGHING)

02:58.012 --> 03:00.974
JARED: <i>The money came raining down,</i>

03:01.057 --> 03:02.559
<i>and for the first time,</i>

03:02.642 --> 03:05.436
<i>the banker went from the country club
to the strip club.</i>

03:08.064 --> 03:11.276
<i>Pretty soon, stocks and savings
were almost inconsequential.</i>

03:11.442 --> 03:13.611
<i>- They were doing $50, $100, $200 billion</i>
- Whoo!

03:13.695 --> 03:16.322
<i>In mortgage bonds and dozens of other
securities a year.</i>

03:16.447 --> 03:17.657
(MEN CHEERING)

03:25.957 --> 03:28.251
<i>And America barely noticed
as its number one industry</i>

03:28.334 --> 03:30.420
<i>became boring old banking.</i>

03:34.090 --> 03:37.594
<i>And then one day,
almost 30 years later, in 2008,</i>

03:38.803 --> 03:40.555
<i>it all came crashing down.</i>

03:43.683 --> 03:46.436
FEMALE REPORTER: <i>March.
Bear Stearns was in a death spiral</i>

03:46.519 --> 03:47.937
<i>and the Fed brokered its sale.</i>

03:48.021 --> 03:51.065
BRIAN WILLIAMS: <i>It's been called the
worst financial crisis in modern times.</i>

03:51.399 --> 03:55.653
<i>Certainly the largest financial disaster
in decades in this country,</i>

03:55.737 --> 03:58.406
<i>and perhaps the end of an era
in American business.</i>

03:58.865 --> 04:01.117
JARED: <i>In the end, Lewis Ranieri's
mortgage-backed security</i>

04:01.200 --> 04:02.869
<i>mutated into a monstrosity that</i>

04:02.994 --> 04:04.662
<i>collapsed the whole world economy.</i>

04:05.330 --> 04:07.330
<i>And none of the experts
or leaders or talking heads</i>

04:07.373 --> 04:08.666
<i>had a clue it was coming.</i>

04:10.168 --> 04:13.129
<i>I'm guessing most of you
still don't really know what happened.</i>

04:13.630 --> 04:16.423
<i>Yeah, you got a soundbite you repeat
so you don't sound dumb, but come on.</i>

04:16.507 --> 04:18.927
Our financial institutions are strong.

04:20.178 --> 04:22.597
<i>But there were some who saw it coming.</i>

04:22.680 --> 04:24.766
<i>While the whole world
was having a big old party,</i>

04:24.849 --> 04:28.102
<i>a few outsiders and weirdos
saw what no one else could.</i>

04:28.186 --> 04:31.773
<i>Not me. I'm not a weirdo.
I'm pretty fucking cool.</i>

04:31.856 --> 04:33.858
<i>But we'll meet again later.</i>

04:34.359 --> 04:37.111
<i>These outsiders saw the giant lie
at the heart of the economy.</i>

04:37.195 --> 04:38.613
<i>And they saw it by doing something</i>

04:38.696 --> 04:41.491
<i>the rest of the suckers
never thought to do.</i>

04:42.408 --> 04:43.743
<i>They looked.</i>

04:49.999 --> 04:52.001
(TAPPING)

04:56.547 --> 04:58.883
MIKE: <i>During the 1930s,</i>

05:00.510 --> 05:05.181
the housing market collapsed nationwide

05:06.557 --> 05:08.685
by roughly 80%.

05:08.768 --> 05:13.898
I mean, half of all mortgage debt
was in default.

05:13.982 --> 05:16.651
And, I mean, there were very

05:17.777 --> 05:21.280
specific identifiers,
extremely recognizable.

05:24.200 --> 05:25.243
I mean, for instance,

05:25.368 --> 05:28.579
(STAMMERING) one of
the hallmarks of mania

05:28.913 --> 05:30.248
is the rapid rise

05:30.373 --> 05:32.417
in complexity and the rates of fraud.

05:32.500 --> 05:35.920
And did you know that they're going up?

05:36.462 --> 05:38.756
(CHEERLEADERS CHEERING)

05:39.757 --> 05:40.758
MAN: Whoo!

05:45.596 --> 05:47.098
(INAUDIBLE)

05:55.440 --> 05:57.358
MIKE: <i>I've always been</i>

05:57.442 --> 05:59.444
<i>more comfortable alone.</i>

05:59.569 --> 06:00.778
(GIRLS TALKING INDISTINCTLY)

06:00.903 --> 06:02.113
(GIRLS LAUGHING)

06:06.743 --> 06:11.372
<i>I believe maybe
it's because of my glass eye.</i>

06:13.791 --> 06:16.586
<i>I lost the eye in a childhood illness.</i>

06:20.923 --> 06:23.259
<i>It separates me from people.</i>

06:27.305 --> 06:29.682
<i>And did you know that they are going</i>

06:29.766 --> 06:30.892
up?

06:30.975 --> 06:34.479
The highest fraud rates since the 1930s.

06:34.562 --> 06:36.898
MIKE'S MOM:
Hey, hey, it's okay. It's okay.

06:36.981 --> 06:38.441
No, I didn't know that.

06:38.566 --> 06:40.026
(MIKE STUTTERING)

06:40.735 --> 06:42.653
(MIKE CHUCKLING)

06:43.154 --> 06:47.325
In 1933, the fourth year
of the Great Depression.

06:47.492 --> 06:49.160
Let's wash it off and put it back in.

06:49.243 --> 06:51.204
MIKE'S DAD: You were
playing so great, son.

06:51.329 --> 06:53.331
I even heard the coach say it.

06:54.499 --> 06:56.751
Can we just go home?

06:56.834 --> 07:01.005
MIKE: <i>Most social interactions
are awkward for me and for the person.</i>

07:01.089 --> 07:04.592
<i>Even when I try to compliment someone,</i>

07:04.675 --> 07:06.052
<i>it comes out wrong.</i>

07:06.969 --> 07:10.556
You have a very nice haircut.
Did you do it yourself?

07:10.973 --> 07:12.642
(CHUCKLES) What?

07:12.725 --> 07:15.228
(STAMMERING) No. No, I...

07:16.229 --> 07:17.563
(SPLASHING)

07:20.608 --> 07:21.848
(TELEPHONE RINGING IN DISTANCE)

07:23.861 --> 07:25.696
I'm sorry. I'm just...

07:28.908 --> 07:30.201
(SIGHS)

07:31.410 --> 07:32.578
I'm going on and on.

07:32.703 --> 07:34.330
My wife told me I need to share more.

07:34.413 --> 07:35.414
Mmm.

07:36.374 --> 07:38.209
- That seems healthy.
- Yeah.

07:38.292 --> 07:39.293
Mmm-hmm.

07:43.631 --> 07:44.799
(CHUCKLES)

07:48.803 --> 07:49.804
Uh...

07:51.013 --> 07:52.390
So do I get the job?

07:52.515 --> 07:54.851
I really think I could help your fund.

07:56.227 --> 07:57.603
Yeah.

07:57.687 --> 07:59.313
Yeah, sure. Go on.

07:59.981 --> 08:01.149
(BOTH CHUCKLING)

08:02.024 --> 08:05.278
- You're...
- David. Great.

08:05.361 --> 08:07.196
I guess I'll go find a desk.

08:07.280 --> 08:09.866
Is there anything you want me
to work on for start...

08:10.366 --> 08:11.367
Uh...

08:12.910 --> 08:14.287
Yeah.

08:14.370 --> 08:16.080
DAVID: You could let me know later.
I could come back.

08:16.372 --> 08:18.332
(STUTTERING)

08:18.791 --> 08:23.337
Did you think it was strange when, um,

08:23.421 --> 08:25.923
the tech bubble burst in 2001

08:26.007 --> 08:28.801
and the housing market in San Jose,

08:28.885 --> 08:31.095
the tech capital of the world,

08:32.597 --> 08:34.347
went up?

08:34.432 --> 08:35.474
Wasn't that strange?

08:35.558 --> 08:36.558
DAVID: No.

08:36.601 --> 08:39.187
No, it's housing.
Housing is always stable.

08:39.270 --> 08:40.313
Low risk. It's solid.

08:40.395 --> 08:42.356
That's the idea, yeah.

08:42.440 --> 08:44.192
I want you to get me

08:44.275 --> 08:47.486
the top 20 selling mortgage bonds.

08:47.570 --> 08:50.406
So you want to know what
the top 20 selling mortgage bonds are?

08:50.489 --> 08:54.827
No, no, no, I want to know
what mortgages are in each one.

08:56.245 --> 08:57.830
(CHUCKLING) Okay, aren't those
mortgages made up of...

08:57.955 --> 08:59.207
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

08:59.290 --> 09:00.750
Wait, aren't those bonds made up

09:00.833 --> 09:02.877
of thousands and thousands
of mortgages?

09:02.960 --> 09:04.420
Yeah.

09:08.466 --> 09:09.967
DAVID: Right away, Dr. Burry.

09:29.028 --> 09:33.366
I am a nice guy all day long.

09:33.449 --> 09:36.118
Ask anyone, I'm a pleasure to work with.

09:38.037 --> 09:42.375
But the second my son screws up, I am...

09:43.042 --> 09:45.544
...yelling at him
just like my dad did to me.

09:48.589 --> 09:50.258
I hear the words that are
coming out of my mouth and...

09:50.341 --> 09:51.592
(DOOR OPENS)

09:51.676 --> 09:54.470
- MARK: Sorry I'm late! No cabs.
- (DOOR CLOSES)

09:55.179 --> 09:56.180
Oh...

09:56.639 --> 09:58.224
So, get this.

09:58.975 --> 10:01.477
I met with this retail banker yesterday.

10:01.727 --> 10:04.146
I'm supposed to be getting him
to invest in a fund,

10:04.230 --> 10:05.564
but instead

10:05.648 --> 10:08.526
I start grilling him about
overdraft penalties

10:08.609 --> 10:11.612
and how his bank will let
a customer write 10-12 checks

10:11.696 --> 10:12.947
before they tell them they're overdrawn.

10:13.030 --> 10:16.951
And this creep is making billions
off screwing over people this way.

10:17.034 --> 10:18.828
And I'm getting madder and madder.

10:18.911 --> 10:22.290
And I ask him,
I look him in the face and I say,

10:22.373 --> 10:24.208
"How can you sleep at night

10:24.709 --> 10:28.170
"knowing that you are
ripping off working people?"

10:28.254 --> 10:29.964
And you know what he did? He left.

10:30.047 --> 10:32.758
He just walks out of the lunch,
doesn't say a word.

10:32.842 --> 10:33.843
What the fuck is that?

10:33.926 --> 10:36.262
Who's fucked up in that scenario? Am I?

10:36.345 --> 10:38.806
Or is this douchebag,
who leaves me hanging?

10:38.889 --> 10:40.141
Is he the fucked up one?

10:40.224 --> 10:43.019
We have talked about this
numerous times.

10:43.102 --> 10:46.230
You can't come in late
and hijack the entire session.

10:46.314 --> 10:47.773
MARK: What do you mean?
I didn't hijack the meeting.

10:47.857 --> 10:48.941
Did I hijack the session?

10:49.066 --> 10:50.192
Yeah.

10:50.651 --> 10:51.819
What do you do?

10:51.944 --> 10:53.112
MAN: I'm in commodities.

10:53.195 --> 10:54.488
Good luck with that.

10:54.572 --> 10:58.159
THERAPIST: Mark, I know
you suffered a terrible loss.

10:58.242 --> 10:59.618
Maybe you want to talk about that.

10:59.702 --> 11:00.786
- I don't talk about that.
- (CELL PHONE CHIMING)

11:00.870 --> 11:02.288
Hold on.

11:02.371 --> 11:03.706
Hold on...

11:03.789 --> 11:06.625
Shit, I have to take this. Sorry. Sorry.

11:07.543 --> 11:09.670
No... (SIGHS) I don't care, Porter.

11:09.754 --> 11:11.339
This guy's whole business
is built on ripping people off.

11:11.422 --> 11:13.007
How long can that last?

11:14.467 --> 11:15.634
Bye, everybody!

11:16.719 --> 11:18.387
MIKE: (SOFTLY) 95...

11:18.637 --> 11:20.765
That's 30 days late... Sixty days late...

11:23.225 --> 11:25.686
They pay on time...

11:25.770 --> 11:26.771
(TYPING ON KEYBOARD)

11:28.606 --> 11:30.232
These FICO scores...

11:31.817 --> 11:32.818
(SIGHS)

11:34.111 --> 11:35.112
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

11:36.822 --> 11:38.949
<i>Late. And they caught up
on their payments...</i>

11:39.033 --> 11:40.534
<i>Another 30 days late...</i>

11:40.618 --> 11:43.871
<i>LTV, 95... LTV, 90...
They caught up on their payments...</i>

11:43.954 --> 11:45.498
<i>Sixty days late? Jesus!</i>

11:45.581 --> 11:47.708
<i>LTV, 110? I've never heard of that!</i>

11:47.792 --> 11:49.126
<i>Thirty days late, rate adjusts...</i>

11:50.127 --> 11:51.379
<i>In '07 rate adjusts...</i>

11:51.462 --> 11:52.630
<i>In '06 rate adjusts...</i>

11:52.755 --> 11:55.049
<i>95... 90... Jesus!</i>

11:55.132 --> 11:56.467
(WHIRRING)

11:56.759 --> 11:58.386
(WHISPERING) He hasn't moved all day.

11:58.469 --> 12:00.805
He does this every few days.

12:00.888 --> 12:02.556
He hasn't spoken to me
since he hired me.

12:02.640 --> 12:04.058
MIKE: <i>Maybe the LTV's at... High-risk,</i>

12:04.141 --> 12:06.394
<i>interest-only... I never heard
of that mortgage history,</i>

12:06.477 --> 12:09.230
<i>I never heard of that... How?</i>

12:09.313 --> 12:10.606
Michael, how are you, guy?

12:10.689 --> 12:13.734
MIKE: <i>Lawrence, I found
something really interesting.</i>

12:13.818 --> 12:15.736
Great, Michael. Whenever you
find something interesting,

12:15.820 --> 12:17.029
<i>we all tend to make money.</i>

12:17.113 --> 12:18.489
<i>What stock are you valuing?</i>

12:18.614 --> 12:19.949
No, no, no, no. No stocks.

12:20.032 --> 12:22.076
I want to short the housing market.

12:22.410 --> 12:23.411
(BRUSHING)

12:23.494 --> 12:26.163
Really? But the housing market
is rock solid.

12:26.664 --> 12:28.082
<i>Greenspan just said</i>

12:28.165 --> 12:30.709
<i>bubbles are regional, defaults are rare.</i>

12:30.835 --> 12:32.962
Tell them I'll be there in a minute.

12:33.045 --> 12:34.839
- Say again?
<i>- Look, look...</i>

12:34.922 --> 12:36.757
(MUFFLED) Greenspan's wrong.

12:36.841 --> 12:40.261
<i>I don't think you mean to do this,
but sometimes you sound very</i>

12:40.344 --> 12:42.638
dismissive and superior.

12:42.721 --> 12:43.889
It's a fact. Greenspan's wrong.

12:43.973 --> 12:46.308
(MUFFLED) I don't know
how else you want me to say...

12:46.392 --> 12:47.768
Look, Michael.

12:47.852 --> 12:49.478
Metro Capital backed you four years ago

12:49.562 --> 12:51.355
<i>when you were a doctor with a</i>

12:51.439 --> 12:53.774
dinky webpage
and some inheritance money.

12:53.858 --> 12:54.859
<i>We've all done very well.</i>

12:54.942 --> 12:56.068
Why don't you just stick with stocks?

12:56.152 --> 12:58.279
<i>Look. You know me. I, I, I...</i>

12:58.362 --> 13:02.116
I look for value wherever it can be found.

13:02.199 --> 13:03.284
And the fact is

13:03.367 --> 13:06.579
that these mortgage-backed
securities are filled

13:06.704 --> 13:10.124
<i>with extremely risky
subprime adjustable-rate loans.</i>

13:10.207 --> 13:12.710
<i>And when the majority
of the adjustable rates</i>

13:12.793 --> 13:15.045
<i>kick in, in '07,</i>

13:15.212 --> 13:16.380
they will begin to fail.

13:16.464 --> 13:19.800
And if they fail above 15%,
the whole bond is worthless.

13:19.884 --> 13:22.052
<i>Michael, just take a beat.</i>

13:22.136 --> 13:23.345
<i>We'll talk about this later, okay?</i>

13:23.429 --> 13:26.474
Lawrence, please,
don't patronize me. Listen...

13:26.557 --> 13:28.017
JARED: <i>Mortgage-backed securities.</i>

13:28.100 --> 13:29.393
It, it, it...

13:29.518 --> 13:31.312
<i>- Subprime loans. Tranches.</i>
- (QUACKING)

13:31.395 --> 13:33.063
<i>It's pretty confusing, right?</i>

13:33.147 --> 13:35.774
<i>Does it make you feel bored?
Or stupid?</i>

13:35.858 --> 13:38.152
<i>Well, it's supposed to.</i>

13:38.235 --> 13:39.835
<i>Wall Street loves to use confusing terms</i>

13:39.904 --> 13:42.573
<i>to make you think only they
can do what they do.</i>

13:42.907 --> 13:44.116
<i>Or, even better,</i>

13:44.200 --> 13:46.577
<i>for you to just leave them the fuck alone.</i>

13:46.660 --> 13:48.621
<i>So here's Margot Robbie
in a bubble bath to explain.</i>

13:48.704 --> 13:49.788
(POPS)

13:49.872 --> 13:52.875
Basically, Lewis Ranieri's
mortgage bonds

13:52.958 --> 13:55.252
were amazingly profitable
for the big banks.

13:55.336 --> 13:59.298
They made billions and billions
on their 2% fee

13:59.381 --> 14:01.592
they got for selling each of these bonds.

14:01.675 --> 14:03.475
But then they started
running out of mortgages

14:03.552 --> 14:05.095
to put in them.

14:05.179 --> 14:07.848
After all, there are only so many homes

14:07.932 --> 14:11.685
and so many people with
good enough jobs to buy them, right?

14:11.769 --> 14:13.854
So the banks started filling these bonds

14:13.938 --> 14:16.106
with riskier and riskier mortgages.

14:16.190 --> 14:17.358
Thank you, Benter.

14:17.441 --> 14:21.987
That way they can keep
that profit machine churning, right?

14:22.071 --> 14:26.450
By the way, these risky mortgages
are called subprime.

14:26.534 --> 14:28.911
So whenever you hear "subprime", think

14:28.994 --> 14:30.454
"shit".

14:30.538 --> 14:34.083
Our friend Michael Burry found out
that these mortgage bonds

14:34.166 --> 14:37.378
that were supposedly 65% AAA

14:37.461 --> 14:40.214
were actually just mostly full of shit.

14:40.798 --> 14:43.551
So now he's going to "short" the bonds.

14:43.634 --> 14:45.636
Which means to "bet against".

14:46.470 --> 14:47.513
Got it?

14:48.222 --> 14:49.473
Good.

14:52.560 --> 14:53.852
Now fuck off.

14:53.936 --> 14:56.272
It's only a matter of time before
someone else sees this investment.

14:56.355 --> 14:58.065
- We have to act now!
- (BANGING TABLE)

14:58.148 --> 15:00.401
How do you know
the bonds are worthless?

15:00.484 --> 15:02.695
Aren't they filled with fucking thousands

15:02.778 --> 15:03.904
<i>of pages of mortgages?</i>

15:03.988 --> 15:06.240
I read them.

15:06.323 --> 15:08.242
<i>- You read them?</i>
- I read... Yes.

15:08.325 --> 15:11.537
No one reads them. Only the lawyers
who put them together read them.

15:11.620 --> 15:16.333
Look, I don't think that they
even know what they've made.

15:16.458 --> 15:19.712
The housing market
is propped up on these

15:20.004 --> 15:22.673
bad loans, and I'm... (SIGHS)

15:22.756 --> 15:24.800
It's a time bomb, and I want to short it.

15:24.883 --> 15:27.177
Through what instrument, Michael?

15:27.261 --> 15:30.264
There are no insurance contracts
or options for mortgage bonds.

15:30.347 --> 15:31.599
The bonds are too stable.

15:31.724 --> 15:33.017
Lawrence...

15:34.143 --> 15:36.020
(STUTTERS)

15:36.353 --> 15:40.190
This is what I'm gonna do.
I am gonna get a bank

15:40.524 --> 15:42.568
to make me one.

15:43.193 --> 15:44.862
And then

15:45.696 --> 15:47.406
I'm gonna buy it.

15:47.740 --> 15:48.741
(CAR HONKING)

15:48.824 --> 15:50.576
MARK: I don't want that kind of business.

15:50.659 --> 15:53.329
Money is not money.
That's bad money.

15:53.996 --> 15:56.206
Hey! Excuse me!

15:57.583 --> 16:00.502
Let me ask you this.
What company treats its customers

16:00.586 --> 16:03.172
that shittily and succeeds?

16:04.048 --> 16:05.883
- Fine. Okay, Goldman. You're right.
- (HORN HONKING)

16:05.966 --> 16:07.301
JARED: <i>Mark Baum had built his career</i>

16:07.384 --> 16:09.428
<i>on never assuming anyone
or any company</i>

16:09.511 --> 16:11.180
<i>was legit without proving it.</i>

16:11.263 --> 16:12.765
<i>When he was a kid
he excelled at studying</i>

16:12.848 --> 16:14.892
<i>the Talmud in Yeshiva. Whatever.</i>

16:14.975 --> 16:16.852
<i>But one day his rabbi told his mom why.</i>

16:16.935 --> 16:17.936
(HORN HONKING)

16:18.062 --> 16:21.065
Paul is a fine boy,
and Mark is an excellent student

16:21.190 --> 16:23.776
of the Torah and the Talmud.

16:23.859 --> 16:25.819
Then what's the problem, rabbi?

16:25.903 --> 16:29.073
It's the reason Mark is studying so hard.

16:29.907 --> 16:33.077
He's looking for inconsistencies
in the word of God!

16:35.829 --> 16:37.998
- So has he found any?
- (SCOFFS)

16:39.083 --> 16:42.336
JARED: <i>Later, Baum started
his own fund on Wall Street.</i>

16:42.419 --> 16:43.859
<i>He had an amazing nose for bullshit.</i>

16:43.921 --> 16:45.923
<i>And he wasn't afraid to let
anyone know when and where</i>

16:46.006 --> 16:48.634
<i>the bull had gone number two.</i>

16:48.717 --> 16:50.344
<i>But then a tragedy happened to Mark,</i>

16:50.427 --> 16:51.887
<i>and it turned his world view dark</i>

16:51.970 --> 16:54.306
<i>and ready to believe
the whole system was a lie.</i>

16:54.390 --> 16:55.933
- (PHONE CHIMES)
- Hold on.

16:56.016 --> 16:58.852
It's Cynthia.
I'll be in the office in 20 minutes.

16:59.770 --> 17:00.938
Hi, honey.

17:01.063 --> 17:02.356
(SIRENS WAILING)

17:02.439 --> 17:06.109
The therapist called. You did it again.

17:06.527 --> 17:09.279
There were no cabs.
What was I supposed to do?

17:09.363 --> 17:11.031
I worry about you, Mark.

17:11.115 --> 17:12.449
<i>At least I went.</i>

17:13.742 --> 17:15.703
You're running around
like you have to right

17:15.786 --> 17:17.621
- every wrong in the world.
- Okay.

17:17.746 --> 17:18.914
<i>You're so angry.</i>

17:18.997 --> 17:20.415
Fine. You know what?

17:20.499 --> 17:23.419
<i>I'm a mean guy and I'm pissed off.</i>

17:23.502 --> 17:25.421
But it is a shit storm out here, sweetie.

17:25.503 --> 17:28.799
You have no idea
the kind of crap people are pulling.

17:28.882 --> 17:31.552
And everyone's walking around like
they're in a goddamn Enya video.

17:31.635 --> 17:33.178
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

17:33.262 --> 17:34.722
They're all getting screwed, you know.

17:34.805 --> 17:37.391
You know what they care about?
They care about the ballgame.

17:37.474 --> 17:40.352
Or they care about
what actress just went into rehab.

17:40.436 --> 17:42.479
I think you should try medication.

17:42.563 --> 17:45.733
No, no. We agreed.
If it interfered with work.

17:45.816 --> 17:47.651
You hate Wall Street.
Maybe it's time to quit.

17:48.152 --> 17:50.112
- I love my job.
- You hate your job.

17:50.195 --> 17:51.196
I love my job.

17:51.280 --> 17:52.280
You're miserable.

17:52.322 --> 17:54.324
I love my job. I love my job, honey.

17:55.284 --> 17:56.577
Mark...

17:57.786 --> 18:00.873
I am sad every day
about what happened.

18:00.956 --> 18:04.293
<i>I know you must feel the same,
but you never show it.</i>

18:10.549 --> 18:13.051
I know how close you
were to your brother.

18:16.430 --> 18:17.514
MARK: <i>Paul.</i>

18:18.557 --> 18:20.184
<i>Where'd you go, Paul?</i>

18:25.439 --> 18:26.690
<i>Paul!</i>

18:32.362 --> 18:35.115
Every day I think you're
gonna talk about it, but you never do.

18:35.407 --> 18:37.659
- (TV PLAYING)
- (TYPING ON LAPTOP)

18:37.743 --> 18:38.744
(BEEPING)

18:38.994 --> 18:42.748
Will you at least think about the idea
of making a change?

18:42.831 --> 18:45.667
<i>Fine. Fine. Honey, you know what?
I will consider it.</i>

18:45.751 --> 18:49.129
But, honestly, Cynthia.
I'm okay. I really am.

18:49.213 --> 18:51.173
Hey, hey, hey! No, no.

18:51.256 --> 18:54.635
My cab. That's my cab.
That's my cab. That is my cab.

18:54.718 --> 18:56.303
MARK: <i>Schmuck. Fuck you.</i>
MAN: <i>Fuck you.</i>

18:56.386 --> 18:57.888
MARK: <i>Fuck you.</i>
MAN: <i>Fuck you.</i>

18:57.971 --> 18:58.972
(PHONE BEEPS)

18:59.056 --> 19:00.557
I'll call you later.

19:03.268 --> 19:04.353
(HORN HONKING)

19:07.940 --> 19:12.027
I want to buy swaps on mortgage bonds.

19:12.110 --> 19:14.446
A credit default swap that will pay off

19:15.489 --> 19:17.991
if the underlying bond fails.

19:18.826 --> 19:20.327
You want to bet against
the housing market?

19:20.410 --> 19:22.371
- Yes.
- Why?

19:22.454 --> 19:23.622
Those bonds only fail

19:23.705 --> 19:26.166
if millions of Americans
don't pay their mortgages.

19:26.250 --> 19:28.669
That's never happened in history.

19:28.752 --> 19:31.672
If you'll excuse me, Dr. Burry,
it seems like a foolish investment.

19:31.755 --> 19:34.508
Well, based on prevailing sentiment

19:34.591 --> 19:36.635
of the market and banks
in popular culture,

19:36.718 --> 19:39.012
yes, it's a foolish investment.

19:39.096 --> 19:41.598
But, uh... Everyone's wrong.

19:41.723 --> 19:43.100
(BOTH LAUGHING)

19:43.183 --> 19:44.685
That's a good one.

19:45.519 --> 19:46.520
(LAUGHS)

19:47.020 --> 19:48.689
This is Wall Street, Dr. Burry.

19:48.772 --> 19:50.732
If you offer us free money,
we are going to take it.

19:50.816 --> 19:55.445
My one concern is that
when the bonds fail,

19:56.572 --> 20:00.117
uh, I want to be certain, um, of payment

20:00.200 --> 20:02.953
um, in case of solvency issues
with your bank.

20:03.954 --> 20:06.331
I'm sorry, are you for real?

20:06.415 --> 20:08.041
You wanna bet against
the housing market

20:08.125 --> 20:09.459
and you're worried we won't pay you?

20:09.543 --> 20:11.128
Yes, that's correct.

20:11.837 --> 20:12.963
(LUCY CLEARS THROAT)

20:15.507 --> 20:16.884
(WHISPERING)

20:22.472 --> 20:24.352
LUCY: (WHISPERING)
...unless the market crashes.

20:24.474 --> 20:26.685
DEEB: (WHISPERS) The market
on housing's never gonna crash

20:26.768 --> 20:29.563
because it's so solid right now.

20:29.646 --> 20:32.399
I mean, who doesn't
pay their mortgages?

20:36.320 --> 20:37.321
Mmm-hmm.

20:39.615 --> 20:40.657
(CLEARS THROAT) Dr. Burry,

20:40.741 --> 20:43.076
we could work out
a pay-as-we-go structure

20:43.160 --> 20:45.162
that would pay out if the bonds fail.

20:45.245 --> 20:46.747
But it would also apply to your payments

20:46.830 --> 20:48.790
if the value of the mortgage bond
goes up.

20:48.874 --> 20:51.585
You'd have to pay us monthly premiums.

20:51.668 --> 20:54.379
LUCY: Is that acceptable, Dr. Burry?

20:56.840 --> 20:58.175
Yes. Yes.

20:59.051 --> 21:01.595
Um, I have prospectuses on six

21:01.678 --> 21:04.556
mortgage-backed securities
I want to short.

21:06.975 --> 21:08.268
(DEEB READING SOFTLY)

21:09.019 --> 21:10.859
LUCY: (WHISPERING)
Majority of the mortgages...

21:11.438 --> 21:12.731
(CHUCKLES)

21:12.856 --> 21:14.191
(LUCY AND DEEB WHISPERING)

21:15.275 --> 21:16.276
(PAGES FLIPPING)

21:22.074 --> 21:24.618
DEEB: (WHISPERING) I don't see us
losing any money on these at all.

21:24.701 --> 21:25.869
(PRINTER WHIRRING)

21:35.295 --> 21:36.296
(INHALES)

21:38.090 --> 21:40.759
Dr. Burry, these should be fine.

21:40.842 --> 21:42.761
Yeah. We're prepared
to sell you $5 million

21:42.844 --> 21:44.724
in credit default swaps
on these mortgage bonds.

21:45.931 --> 21:47.349
Can we make it $100 million?

21:50.227 --> 21:52.604
Uh, absolutely,
we can make it $100 million.

21:54.189 --> 21:57.401
LUCY: We'll be in touch,
send some paperwork over.

21:58.235 --> 21:59.236
DEEB: Um...

22:00.362 --> 22:01.738
(SIGHING) I like these cups.

22:01.822 --> 22:03.490
(STUTTERING)
Can I take one for my son?

22:03.573 --> 22:05.325
LUCY: Have... Yes. Yes.

22:05.409 --> 22:06.910
Thank you.

22:06.994 --> 22:08.370
LUCY: Have two.

22:13.792 --> 22:16.545
(INAUDIBLE)

22:16.962 --> 22:18.547
(HIP HOP MUSIC PLAYING)

22:28.348 --> 22:31.351
Is there any way to do $200 million?

22:32.811 --> 22:35.439
I mean, we can. But are you sure?

22:36.356 --> 22:39.526
Absolutely. Absolutely, we can do that.

22:53.248 --> 22:56.626
We do different projects.
We do gardening.

22:56.710 --> 22:59.963
The bonds I'd like to bet against.

23:00.172 --> 23:01.673
It's not bad seeing yourself
on the big screen.

23:01.757 --> 23:02.758
It's very cool.

23:03.800 --> 23:07.471
<i>I ordered the 24-ounce T-bone,
which was choice.</i>

23:07.554 --> 23:09.014
<i>- I went for volume...</i>
- WOMAN: <i>Yeah.</i>

23:09.097 --> 23:10.724
<i>...rather than prime.</i>

23:10.807 --> 23:13.477
I went for subprime, and the gist was...

23:18.940 --> 23:19.941
(HORN HONKING)

23:20.817 --> 23:23.320
MAN: Can I have like, lettuce,
tomato, no onions?

23:23.945 --> 23:27.240
WOMAN: So, no onions.
Lettuce, tomato, Thousand Island okay?

23:27.324 --> 23:28.325
MAN: Yeah.

23:32.162 --> 23:33.705
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

23:35.373 --> 23:37.084
Hey, Randall! What's with the Dom?

23:37.167 --> 23:39.044
Bonuses aren't for three months.

23:39.127 --> 23:43.090
We just sold $200 million
in credit swaps for mortgage bonds.

23:43.173 --> 23:45.342
Some fund manager from California.

23:45.467 --> 23:46.802
It's fucking crazy, right?

23:46.885 --> 23:47.969
A whole new way to make money, Doug.

23:48.053 --> 23:50.305
Wait, wait. I didn't know
there were swaps on mortgages.

23:50.388 --> 23:52.974
(LAUGHS) There are now.
We made it for him.

23:53.058 --> 23:54.726
He must have gone off
his Zoloft or something.

23:54.810 --> 23:56.144
I don't know. (CHUCKLES)

23:56.228 --> 23:57.979
- Want to join? No?
- Just a second.

23:58.063 --> 23:59.064
Oh...

23:59.231 --> 24:00.649
DOUG: Hey, Jared.

24:00.732 --> 24:02.192
Did you hear about the deal
that Randall just did

24:02.275 --> 24:03.485
with some fund manager?

24:03.568 --> 24:05.362
JARED: Randall? Bullshit.

24:05.821 --> 24:07.661
He's a foot soldier.
I'm sure it's a shit deal.

24:07.739 --> 24:08.990
No, it's for real.

24:10.200 --> 24:11.618
I told you we'd meet later.

24:11.701 --> 24:14.121
Unfortunately, it's in a place like this
which I would never be.

24:14.204 --> 24:16.873
I never hung out with
these idiots after work, ever.

24:16.957 --> 24:18.750
I had fashion friends.

24:19.167 --> 24:22.504
Apparently, this guy wanted $200 mil
in credit default swaps.

24:22.587 --> 24:24.339
Randall made the sale.
Can you believe it?

24:24.422 --> 24:26.633
Somebody shorted $200 mil
on mortgage bonds?

24:26.716 --> 24:30.137
That was just with Deutsche.
Word is he hit half the town.

24:31.012 --> 24:32.139
How much in total?

24:32.222 --> 24:33.932
$1.3 billion.

24:34.015 --> 24:37.853
LAWRENCE: <i>What? That's pretty much
all of Scion's liquidity.</i>

24:37.936 --> 24:40.021
Michael, this is highly distressing.

24:40.105 --> 24:41.523
<i>Lawrence, that is not</i>

24:41.606 --> 24:44.151
all of our liquidity.

24:44.234 --> 24:45.443
And I'm not certain

24:45.527 --> 24:47.737
<i>that you really understand this trade.</i>

24:47.863 --> 24:48.905
This is a certainty.

24:48.989 --> 24:52.075
<i>Mike, I consider myself a mentor to you.</i>

24:52.159 --> 24:55.996
<i>But our company is not comfortable
with this investment. Am I being clear?</i>

24:56.079 --> 24:58.331
Lawrence, I have full autonomy

24:58.415 --> 25:01.334
when it comes to investment strategy.

25:01.418 --> 25:02.544
(SIGHS) You can read our agreement.

25:02.627 --> 25:05.964
<i>Do not throw our inception agreement
in my face, Michael.</i>

25:06.047 --> 25:08.425
<i>- We had an underlying understanding</i>
- (COMPUTER BEEPS)

25:08.592 --> 25:09.801
<i>you wouldn't act like
a goddamn crazy man.</i>

25:09.885 --> 25:11.469
This is not crazy.

25:11.553 --> 25:13.013
It's all very logical.

25:13.096 --> 25:15.307
<i>So, now we pay up premiums
on these swaps</i>

25:15.891 --> 25:18.643
against the housing market
until the mortgages fail?

25:18.727 --> 25:20.395
In other words, we lose millions

25:20.520 --> 25:23.190
<i>until something that's
never happened before happens?</i>

25:27.068 --> 25:28.069
That's correct.

25:32.365 --> 25:34.075
(TELEPHONES RINGING)

26:01.603 --> 26:02.854
KATHY: Hello, Mark Baum.

26:02.938 --> 26:05.023
Oh, hey, Kathy, you busted me.

26:05.106 --> 26:06.066
I had a personal thing this afternoon.

26:06.149 --> 26:07.150
I'm not your babysitter.

26:07.234 --> 26:09.861
If FrontPoint makes money
for Morgan Stanley, I'm happy.

26:09.945 --> 26:12.239
Okay. Hey, did I hear you're expecting?

26:12.322 --> 26:13.698
We're expecting to be expecting.

26:13.782 --> 26:15.450
IVF's are cleaning us out
but we're staying positive...

26:15.533 --> 26:17.035
That's exciting!

26:18.328 --> 26:19.329
(CHUCKLES)

26:21.164 --> 26:24.167
...lump on my ball.
And I go in for a scan.

26:24.292 --> 26:25.293
Mmm-hmm.

26:25.377 --> 26:29.089
Turns out that I have a very large thing
called an epididymis.

26:29.172 --> 26:31.716
Which is a thing
that goes around the ball

26:31.800 --> 26:33.510
and is like a sac underneath.

26:33.593 --> 26:34.636
I have an extremely

26:34.719 --> 26:36.554
- pronounced epididymis.
- PORTER: I'm riveted...

26:36.638 --> 26:38.682
I'm riveted by this.
Do you have any pictures?

26:38.765 --> 26:42.310
DANNY: It's almost as large
as another testicle unto itself.

26:42.394 --> 26:44.479
So get this. Cynthia...

26:44.562 --> 26:47.607
Guys. Cynthia wants me to quit
and open a B&B in Vermont.

26:47.691 --> 26:48.817
(VINNIE LAUGHING)

26:48.900 --> 26:52.279
That sounds great. I'd love to see
Mark Baum run a bed and breakfast.

26:52.362 --> 26:54.322
Like, "Here's your
steel-cut oatmeal, asshole."

26:54.406 --> 26:56.992
JARED: <i>Mark refused to kiss the ring
of the people with the checkbooks,</i>

26:57.075 --> 27:00.120
<i>so he had to set up his fund
under Morgan Stanley's umbrella.</i>

27:00.203 --> 27:01.288
(LAUGHING)

27:01.371 --> 27:03.915
<i>His small team reflected
his distrust of the system.</i>

27:03.999 --> 27:05.417
You guys are sick. You're sick.

27:05.542 --> 27:07.669
She says this job is making me unhappy.

27:07.752 --> 27:08.795
VINNIE: But you're happy
when you're unhappy.

27:08.878 --> 27:10.380
I am happy when I'm unhappy.

27:10.463 --> 27:11.464
JARED: <i>Vinnie Daniel.</i>

27:11.548 --> 27:12.674
You know how to make a muffin?

27:12.757 --> 27:14.477
<i>- Mark's numbers guy.</i>
- Do you even know how

27:14.551 --> 27:16.011
- to do laundry? Make a bed?
- MARK: Okay...

27:16.094 --> 27:18.722
<i>Vinnie lost his father to a violent crime
when he was young.</i>

27:18.805 --> 27:20.640
<i>Just like Mark, he didn't talk about it.</i>

27:20.724 --> 27:21.975
I don't talk about that.

27:22.058 --> 27:24.394
Cynthia's no joke. She could
actually make him move to Vermont.

27:24.477 --> 27:26.146
I mean, she made me
start wearing a seatbelt.

27:26.229 --> 27:27.939
- Hey, you want me to...
- JARED: <i>Porter Collins.</i>

27:28.064 --> 27:30.233
<i>Former Olympic rower
who went to Brown.</i>

27:30.317 --> 27:31.985
<i>He worked with Baum at a previous firm</i>

27:32.068 --> 27:33.987
<i>and couldn't figure out
why no one listened to Baum.</i>

27:34.070 --> 27:36.156
<i>The guy with all the good ideas.</i>

27:36.239 --> 27:38.033
Sorry. I think you have
the wrong FrontPoint.

27:38.158 --> 27:40.958
'Cause there is another FrontPoint
in this same building that is bonds.

27:40.994 --> 27:43.747
<i>And Danny Moses.
The optimist of the bunch.</i>

27:44.664 --> 27:45.874
<i>And a hell of a trader.</i>

27:45.957 --> 27:49.085
<i>Which is the only reason they put up
with his bullshit optimism.</i>

27:49.169 --> 27:50.420
DANNY: That was a weird call.

27:50.503 --> 27:53.798
You take longer with a wrong number
than anybody else.

27:53.882 --> 27:56.509
It was this guy from Deutsche

27:56.593 --> 27:59.179
who was talking about
shorting housing bonds.

28:00.555 --> 28:01.723
And then in the middle of the call

28:01.848 --> 28:03.016
I realized he had the wrong FrontPoint.

28:03.099 --> 28:05.435
And then... 'Cause he wanted
the one on the 8th floor.

28:06.102 --> 28:08.021
He wanted to short housing bonds?

28:08.104 --> 28:09.147
Uh-huh. That happens
like five times a day

28:09.230 --> 28:10.690
that somebody gets
the wrong FrontPoint.

28:10.774 --> 28:12.942
- We should change our name.
- VINNIE: Wait. Wait.

28:13.026 --> 28:14.986
He wanted to short housing bonds?

28:15.278 --> 28:17.238
- Who bets against housing?
- (TYPING ON COMPUTER)

28:18.031 --> 28:19.240
VINNIE: What's the ABX at?

28:19.366 --> 28:20.533
What's ABX?

28:20.617 --> 28:23.453
It tracks subprime mortgage bond value.
Go back to sleep.

28:23.870 --> 28:26.164
- The ABX is at, uh...
- (BEEPING)

28:26.289 --> 28:29.542
Wow, it's down! It's down
three points since last year.

28:29.626 --> 28:31.878
That's weird. I haven't
heard a peep about that.

28:31.961 --> 28:33.004
What was this guy's name?

28:33.088 --> 28:35.215
Jared Vennett. Vennett.

28:35.298 --> 28:37.550
JARED: <i>That's right.
These lucky sons of bitches</i>

28:37.634 --> 28:40.387
<i>caught wind of one of the best trades
in Wall Street history</i>

28:40.470 --> 28:42.055
<i>from a wrong number.</i>

28:42.138 --> 28:44.391
<i>They should have paid 10%
to my fuckstick assistant.</i>

28:44.474 --> 28:46.810
DANNY: His name was
Jared Vennett. Vennett.

28:46.893 --> 28:48.728
Jared Vennett from Deutsche.
Sounded very sketchy.

28:48.812 --> 28:50.092
VINNIE: Sounds like a douchebag.

28:50.647 --> 28:52.440
(WHISPERING) Do you smell that?

28:52.524 --> 28:53.858
Do you smell that?

28:53.983 --> 28:55.235
I smell money.

28:56.027 --> 28:57.445
This is your basic mortgage...

29:01.241 --> 29:03.410
Okay, hi. How are you?

29:03.952 --> 29:05.161
Have a seat.

29:05.245 --> 29:07.997
MARK: Okay, Mr. Vennett
from Deutsche Bank. What do we have?

29:12.544 --> 29:14.129
There you go.

29:17.590 --> 29:20.135
MARK: So, how many people
have you talked to about this trade?

29:20.218 --> 29:22.971
A few. There's definitely some interest.

29:23.054 --> 29:24.472
- No!
- My boss would have my ass...

29:24.556 --> 29:25.974
- N.O.!
- You crazy, Jared?

29:26.057 --> 29:27.600
- Get lost.
- Fuck you.

29:28.351 --> 29:31.146
Which is why you're here talking to us,
a wrong number.

29:31.229 --> 29:32.647
Sounds like there's a lot of interest.

29:32.730 --> 29:35.066
All right. A few people have invited us in

29:35.150 --> 29:37.527
just to laugh at me on this deal.
Is that you?

29:37.610 --> 29:38.611
Is that what this is?

29:38.695 --> 29:39.737
VINNIE: That's not what this is.

29:39.821 --> 29:41.614
That's just how Mark is.

29:41.698 --> 29:42.991
- Let's see what you got.
- I'm sorry.

29:43.074 --> 29:44.742
You smell that? What is that?

29:44.868 --> 29:46.286
- MARK: What?
- What's that smell?

29:46.703 --> 29:47.704
Your cologne?

29:47.787 --> 29:48.830
JARED: No.

29:51.082 --> 29:52.375
Opportunity.

29:52.500 --> 29:53.793
No. Money.

29:53.877 --> 29:55.170
- Oh...
- MARK: Okay.

29:55.253 --> 29:56.796
- I smell money.
- Okay.

29:57.297 --> 29:59.966
- Chris, God damn it.
- Sorry.

30:03.178 --> 30:05.597
JARED: This is your
basic mortgage bond.

30:05.680 --> 30:07.932
All right? The originals were simple.

30:08.016 --> 30:11.686
They were just thousands
of AAA mortgages bundled together,

30:11.769 --> 30:13.521
guaranteed by the U.S. government.

30:13.605 --> 30:15.440
The modern ones are different.

30:15.523 --> 30:18.443
They're private. And they're
made up of layers of tranches.

30:23.698 --> 30:26.117
The highest level, AAA,
is getting paid first.

30:26.201 --> 30:29.370
The lowest rated, B, is getting paid last,
taking on defaults first.

30:29.454 --> 30:32.123
Now, obviously, if you're buying B's,
you could make more money.

30:32.207 --> 30:33.374
But they're a little risky.

30:33.458 --> 30:35.627
Sometimes they fail.

30:36.878 --> 30:38.213
Chris?

30:42.050 --> 30:44.302
Somewhere along the line,
these B's and BB's

30:44.385 --> 30:45.845
went from a little risky

30:45.929 --> 30:48.348
to dog shit. Where's the trash?

30:48.431 --> 30:49.631
PORTER: It's right behind you.

30:49.807 --> 30:52.685
I'm talking rock-bottom FICO scores.

30:52.769 --> 30:53.770
(THUNKING)

30:53.895 --> 30:55.396
No income verification.

30:55.480 --> 30:56.523
(THUNKING)

30:56.606 --> 30:59.442
Adjustable rates. Dog shit!

31:00.902 --> 31:03.738
The default rates are already up
from 1% to 4%, fellas.

31:03.821 --> 31:06.032
And if they rise to 8%, and they will,

31:06.824 --> 31:09.077
a lot of these BBB's
are going to zero, too.

31:09.160 --> 31:10.578
And that... You're too close.

31:12.330 --> 31:13.331
...is an opportunity.

31:13.414 --> 31:14.414
- (EXHALES)
- MARK: Okay.

31:14.457 --> 31:18.086
You're saying that at 8% the bonds fail
and we are already at 4%?

31:18.169 --> 31:19.170
That's right.

31:19.254 --> 31:21.047
If they go to 8%, it's Armageddon?

31:21.130 --> 31:22.131
Yeah. That's right.

31:22.257 --> 31:23.967
How come nobody's talking about this?

31:24.092 --> 31:26.219
You're completely sure of the math?

31:26.302 --> 31:28.888
Look at him. That's my quant.

31:28.972 --> 31:30.014
MARK: Your what?

31:30.098 --> 31:31.891
My quantitative!

31:31.975 --> 31:34.644
My math specialist. Look at him.

31:34.769 --> 31:37.105
You notice anything different about him?
Look at his face.

31:37.188 --> 31:38.268
MARK: That's pretty racist.

31:38.314 --> 31:40.817
JARED: Look at his eyes!
I'll give you a hint.

31:40.900 --> 31:42.443
His name's Yang!

31:43.611 --> 31:46.906
He won a national
math competition in China!

31:46.990 --> 31:49.492
He doesn't even speak English!

31:49.576 --> 31:51.244
Yeah, I'm sure of the math.

31:52.954 --> 31:56.749
Actually, my name's Jiang
and I do speak English.

31:56.833 --> 31:58.293
Jared likes to say I don't
because he thinks

31:58.376 --> 32:00.211
it makes me seem more authentic.

32:00.295 --> 32:02.839
And I got second in that
national math competition.

32:03.423 --> 32:08.303
So you're offering us a chance
to short this pile of blocks? How?

32:08.386 --> 32:10.847
With something called
a credit default swap.

32:10.930 --> 32:12.056
(CLAPS HANDS)

32:12.140 --> 32:14.642
It's like insurance on the bond,
and if it goes bust

32:14.726 --> 32:17.895
you can make 10-to-1,
even 20-to-1 return.

32:17.979 --> 32:20.106
And it's already slowly going bust!

32:20.356 --> 32:22.442
10-to-1? 20-to-1? No way.

32:22.525 --> 32:24.485
JARED: And no one's paying attention.

32:24.986 --> 32:27.405
No one is paying attention!

32:27.488 --> 32:30.950
Because the banks are too busy
getting paid obscene fees

32:31.034 --> 32:32.327
to sell these bonds.

32:32.410 --> 32:35.163
But wait. You are the bank.
You work for the bank.

32:35.246 --> 32:37.290
I bet your margins are pretty nice and fat.

32:37.373 --> 32:39.667
Let's not talk about
my margins, by the way.

32:39.751 --> 32:41.794
Being nice and fat, that's a nice shirt.
Do they make it for men?

32:41.878 --> 32:43.087
(DANNY AND PORTER SNICKERING)

32:43.171 --> 32:44.130
VINNIE: Aren't you the bank?

32:44.213 --> 32:47.133
I work for the bank.
I don't think like a bank.

32:47.216 --> 32:51.095
Big bank, small bank,
I like to make money. All right?

32:51.179 --> 32:53.890
Let me put it this way.
I'm standing in front of a burning house...

32:54.015 --> 32:56.768
And I'm offering you fire insurance on it.

32:56.851 --> 32:59.354
How can these underlying bonds
be as bad as you say?

32:59.479 --> 33:00.688
It wouldn't be legal.
(CLEARS THROAT)

33:00.772 --> 33:02.732
Nobody knows what's in them.

33:02.815 --> 33:04.317
Nobody knows what's in the bonds.

33:04.400 --> 33:07.487
I've seen some that are 65% AAA-rated

33:07.570 --> 33:10.531
that I know for a fact are filled with 95%

33:10.615 --> 33:13.409
subprime shit with FICOs below 550!

33:13.868 --> 33:14.994
Get the fuck out of here.

33:15.078 --> 33:16.454
You want me to really blow your mind?

33:16.537 --> 33:18.081
When the market deems
a bond too risky to buy,

33:18.164 --> 33:20.375
what do you think we do with it?

33:20.458 --> 33:21.584
Take a guess.

33:21.668 --> 33:23.086
I don't know. You tell me.

33:23.169 --> 33:27.090
All right. You think we just
warehouse it on the books? No.

33:27.173 --> 33:29.092
We just repackage it
with a bunch of other shit

33:29.175 --> 33:31.260
that didn't sell and put it into a CDO.

33:32.095 --> 33:34.138
MARK: A CDO?
JARED: Yes. A CDO.

33:34.931 --> 33:36.683
- What is that?
- This is where we take a bunch of B's,

33:36.766 --> 33:38.935
BB's and BBB's that haven't sold,

33:39.018 --> 33:40.698
- and we put them in a pile.
- (CLATTERING)

33:42.230 --> 33:44.190
JARED: And when the pile
gets large enough,

33:44.315 --> 33:46.859
the whole thing is suddenly
considered diversified

33:46.943 --> 33:51.656
and the whores at the rating agency
give it a 92%-93% AAA rating,

33:51.739 --> 33:53.741
no questions asked.

33:54.158 --> 33:55.159
(EXHALES)

33:55.410 --> 33:57.912
Hold it. What? Say that again.

33:58.204 --> 34:00.456
A collateralized debt obligation.

34:00.540 --> 34:02.041
It's important to understand
because it's what allowed

34:02.125 --> 34:06.254
a housing crisis to become
a nationwide economic disaster.

34:06.337 --> 34:09.549
Here's world-famous chef
Anthony Bourdain to explain.

34:09.674 --> 34:11.050
(LAUGHS)

34:14.137 --> 34:15.804
ANTHONY: Okay, I'm a chef
on a Sunday afternoon

34:15.972 --> 34:17.639
setting the menu at a big restaurant.

34:17.806 --> 34:19.225
I ordered my fish on Friday,

34:19.308 --> 34:22.018
which is the mortgage bond
that Michael Burry shorted.

34:22.228 --> 34:24.230
But some of the fresh fish doesn't sell.

34:24.313 --> 34:25.940
I don't know why.
Maybe it just came out

34:26.065 --> 34:27.745
halibut has the intelligence of a dolphin.

34:27.775 --> 34:29.485
So, what am I going to do?

34:29.569 --> 34:33.072
Throw all this unsold fish,
which is the BBB level of the bond,

34:33.156 --> 34:35.616
in the garbage and take the loss?

34:36.576 --> 34:37.577
No way.

34:37.659 --> 34:40.079
Being the crafty
and morally onerous chef that I am,

34:40.163 --> 34:42.831
whatever crappy levels
of the bond I don't sell,

34:42.956 --> 34:44.917
I throw into a seafood stew.

34:45.001 --> 34:48.420
See, it's not old fish.
It's a whole new thing!

34:48.504 --> 34:52.216
And the best part is
they're eating 3-day-old halibut.

34:52.300 --> 34:53.967
That is a CDO.

34:54.092 --> 34:56.929
PORTER: I just need to know,
how could these possibly be collated?

34:57.013 --> 34:59.432
Somehow you're like Dora the Explorer

34:59.515 --> 35:00.767
and you're the first person

35:00.850 --> 35:02.185
- who found this thing.
- Hold on. Hold on.

35:02.268 --> 35:04.145
So mortgage bonds are dog shit,

35:04.228 --> 35:06.439
CDOs are dog shit wrapped in cat shit.

35:06.522 --> 35:07.523
(BUZZING)

35:07.982 --> 35:09.817
Yeah, that's right.

35:09.901 --> 35:13.404
Institutions treat these CDOs
like they're as solid as treasury bonds,

35:13.488 --> 35:14.739
and they're going to zero.

35:14.822 --> 35:15.865
(CLATTERING)

35:15.948 --> 35:18.159
DANNY: No. That can't be right.
There were $500 billion

35:18.242 --> 35:20.578
in housing bonds sold last year alone.

35:20.870 --> 35:23.498
The rating agencies, the banks,
the fucking government,

35:23.581 --> 35:25.583
you're saying they're
all asleep at the wheel?

35:25.666 --> 35:29.128
Yeah. My whole department's
long on this stuff.

35:30.004 --> 35:33.883
They call me Chicken Little.
They call me Bubble Boy.

35:36.552 --> 35:39.972
- A's, zero. B's, zero.
- (CLATTERING)

35:40.264 --> 35:43.518
BB's, zero. BBB's, zero.

35:45.937 --> 35:47.313
And then that happens.

35:47.396 --> 35:49.065
What is that?

35:50.942 --> 35:52.652
That's America's housing market.

35:55.613 --> 35:56.656
Thank you.

35:56.739 --> 35:57.740
Fuckin' A, Jared.

35:57.824 --> 35:59.826
Shut your fucking mouth.

35:59.909 --> 36:02.078
- ...hang out with you.
- MARK: Good. Okay.

36:02.203 --> 36:04.330
JARED: Sack up, do the deal.
Let's be friends.

36:04.413 --> 36:05.623
MARK: We will see. Thank you.

36:05.706 --> 36:06.749
JARED: Don't bullshit me.
MARK: All right.

36:06.833 --> 36:07.917
JARED: You're gonna say no, aren't you?

36:08.042 --> 36:10.503
MIKE: No. No, I'm just
evaluating right now.

36:10.586 --> 36:12.626
- Thank you. Thank you for coming in.
- (DOOR OPENS)

36:13.381 --> 36:14.715
Bye, Jared.

36:20.763 --> 36:22.181
VINNIE: I don't like it.

36:23.140 --> 36:24.809
He's playing us.

36:25.935 --> 36:27.770
He's playing us.
He's got too much skin in the game

36:27.854 --> 36:29.522
and he's dumping his position.

36:30.481 --> 36:31.983
What if he's right?

36:32.066 --> 36:33.150
You want him to be right.

36:33.234 --> 36:34.777
MARK: Yes, I do.

36:35.361 --> 36:38.447
The banks have given us
25% interest rates on credit cards.

36:38.531 --> 36:40.241
They have screwed us on student loans

36:40.324 --> 36:42.076
that we can never get out from under.

36:42.159 --> 36:45.371
Then this guy walks into
my office and says

36:45.454 --> 36:48.416
those same banks got greedy,
they lost track of the market,

36:48.499 --> 36:50.543
and I can profit off of their stupidity?

36:50.626 --> 36:52.879
Fuck, yeah, I want him to be right!

36:52.962 --> 36:54.213
VINNIE: How come you
don't hate this guy?

36:54.297 --> 36:55.977
He's everything
you taught us not to trust.

36:56.048 --> 36:57.758
I can't hate him.
He is so transparent

36:57.842 --> 37:00.219
in his self-interest
that I kind of respect him.

37:00.303 --> 37:03.389
- Would I buy a car from him? No.
- (PORTER CHUCKLES)

37:03.639 --> 37:04.891
Is he right about the mortgage market?

37:04.974 --> 37:07.184
- No.
- Let's find out. Let's find out.

37:08.769 --> 37:10.605
Look. It's two very simple questions.

37:10.688 --> 37:12.189
Is there a housing bubble?

37:12.273 --> 37:14.859
And if there is,
how exposed are the banks?

37:14.942 --> 37:15.985
PORTER: Yeah. Okay.

37:16.068 --> 37:17.486
Let's get on this quickly too.

37:17.570 --> 37:18.946
Because if he's right,

37:19.030 --> 37:22.491
every loser with a couple million bucks
and a fund is gonna be jumping on this.

37:23.034 --> 37:24.035
Let's go.

37:25.036 --> 37:26.037
(ELEVATOR DINGS)

37:26.329 --> 37:27.830
WOMAN: Just that morning...

37:29.332 --> 37:31.125
(BREATHING DEEPLY)

37:32.001 --> 37:35.338
JPMorgan Chase. JPMorgan Chase.

37:37.173 --> 37:39.467
JAMIE: Okay. Stop saying
"JPMorgan Chase".

37:39.550 --> 37:40.968
I got a good feeling about this.

37:41.052 --> 37:42.532
It's just a meeting though, you know?

37:43.262 --> 37:44.764
It's just a meeting. It's something like...

37:44.847 --> 37:46.974
People have meetings
all the time. You know?

37:47.058 --> 37:48.684
People drink their coffee,
they have a meeting.

37:48.768 --> 37:50.128
CHRIS: Brownfield Fund?
JAMIE: Yes!

37:50.186 --> 37:52.063
- Hey. Hello.
- CHARLIE: Ted.

37:52.146 --> 37:53.481
Chris. I'm on Ted's desk.

37:53.606 --> 37:54.941
Chris. Okay.

37:55.024 --> 37:56.192
- I'm Charlie, Charlie Geller.
- Charlie.

37:56.275 --> 37:57.902
- Jamie Shipley. Hi.
- Jamie.

37:57.985 --> 38:00.947
We're so excited to get set up
on your trading platform.

38:01.030 --> 38:02.156
Cool.

38:02.239 --> 38:04.033
Here, have a seat a second.

38:04.784 --> 38:05.785
All right.

38:06.869 --> 38:09.789
So, I... Ted had asked me
to do some meeting prep.

38:09.872 --> 38:13.250
But I couldn't find
any marketing material on you guys.

38:13.334 --> 38:15.169
We just moved here from Boulder.

38:15.252 --> 38:16.754
- Yeah.
- Got it.

38:16.837 --> 38:19.215
Could we see some
of your offering documents?

38:19.298 --> 38:21.801
Well, Brownfield is its own money.

38:22.385 --> 38:24.095
- It's our money.
- Yeah.

38:24.178 --> 38:25.972
Can you tell us how much you manage?

38:26.055 --> 38:29.517
Of course. We're doing
$30 million right now.

38:29.600 --> 38:30.810
Um, but we started

38:30.893 --> 38:33.646
- four years ago with $110,000.
- CHRIS: Wow.

38:33.729 --> 38:38.359
So, as you can see,
that's pretty phenomenal returns.

38:38.442 --> 38:41.654
We want to get an ISDA agreement
with JPMorgan so we can

38:41.779 --> 38:44.281
deal in long-term options.

38:44.365 --> 38:45.700
- That's really cool.
- Yeah.

38:58.587 --> 39:00.381
That is so cool.

39:00.464 --> 39:01.549
Thank you.

39:01.632 --> 39:05.803
But you guys are under
the capital requirements for an ISDA.

39:05.928 --> 39:06.929
By how much?

39:07.596 --> 39:08.597
Uh...

39:08.806 --> 39:12.184
One billion four hundred
seventy million, so...

39:13.185 --> 39:14.729
...a lot.

39:15.980 --> 39:17.440
This makes us look bad, doesn't it,

39:17.523 --> 39:20.693
that we didn't know
what the capital requirements were?

39:20.776 --> 39:21.777
Uh...

39:22.361 --> 39:23.779
It's not great.

39:24.280 --> 39:25.573
But, uh,

39:25.656 --> 39:28.117
keep up those returns and give us a call

39:28.200 --> 39:29.994
way down the line. You know.

39:30.077 --> 39:31.078
Okay?

39:31.162 --> 39:32.455
- Okay.
- Thanks, Chris.

39:32.580 --> 39:33.580
Have a good one, guys.

39:33.622 --> 39:34.665
CHARLIE: Thank you, Chris.

39:37.168 --> 39:38.169
(SIGHS)

39:38.961 --> 39:39.962
Shit!

39:41.130 --> 39:42.410
Who the fuck schedules a meeting

39:42.465 --> 39:44.592
- at 4:50 in the afternoon?
- Oh, my, God.

39:44.675 --> 39:46.427
That was so painful.

39:46.510 --> 39:50.139
Dude, B of A and Bear
didn't even return our calls.

39:50.222 --> 39:52.391
And even fucking Wachovia

39:52.475 --> 39:54.143
- blew us off, man!
- I know.

39:54.310 --> 39:56.562
Here's the prospectuses
of all the other losers

39:56.645 --> 39:58.355
who didn't make it past the lobby.

39:58.439 --> 40:00.316
JAMIE: I don't think I can
do this anymore. You know.

40:00.399 --> 40:03.235
I'm young, yet.
I can still do something with my life.

40:03.319 --> 40:05.404
I miss Colorado anyway.
The weed's better.

40:06.363 --> 40:08.365
Gentlemen, I need you to leave.

40:08.491 --> 40:09.867
Yep, yep, we're going. Let's go.

40:09.992 --> 40:11.118
Look at this. Look at this.

40:11.202 --> 40:12.536
This guy

40:12.620 --> 40:15.539
says that the housing market's
a giant bubble.

40:16.832 --> 40:17.833
(INHALES)

40:17.917 --> 40:20.086
Okay, so this part
isn't totally accurate, you know.

40:20.169 --> 40:22.254
We didn't find Jared Vennett's
housing bubble pitch

40:22.338 --> 40:24.256
in the lobby of a bank that rejected us.

40:24.340 --> 40:25.800
The truth is, um,

40:25.883 --> 40:28.761
a friend had told Charlie about it,
and I read about it

40:28.844 --> 40:30.262
in <i>Grant's Interest Rate Observer.</i>

40:30.346 --> 40:31.680
This is crazy.

40:31.764 --> 40:34.266
This is crazy stuff.

40:34.350 --> 40:37.019
Shit, he's saying
that there's 10-to-1 returns

40:37.103 --> 40:40.731
on credit default swaps
for mortgage-backed securities?

40:40.856 --> 40:43.484
And the whole housing market
is about to collapse?

40:44.193 --> 40:45.945
JARED: <i>For Jamie and Charlie,
the housing market</i>

40:46.028 --> 40:48.447
<i>doomsday prediction
was music to their ears.</i>

40:48.531 --> 40:50.241
(SINGING)

40:56.080 --> 40:58.040
<i>They had started working
out of Jamie's garage</i>

40:58.124 --> 41:00.042
<i>with $110,000 Jamie had saved</i>

41:00.126 --> 41:02.211
<i>taking sailboats up and down
the East Coast.</i>

41:04.130 --> 41:05.923
Our investment strategy was simple.

41:06.006 --> 41:08.050
People hate to think about
bad things happening,

41:08.134 --> 41:10.469
so they always underestimate
their likelihood.

41:10.553 --> 41:13.055
JARED: <i>Their strategy
was simple and brilliant.</i>

41:13.597 --> 41:14.682
What he said.

41:14.765 --> 41:17.476
<i>Jamie and Charlie found markets
will sell options very cheaply</i>

41:17.560 --> 41:19.770
<i>on things they think will never happen.</i>

41:19.854 --> 41:21.438
<i>So when they were wrong,
they were wrong small,</i>

41:21.522 --> 41:23.482
<i>but when they were right,
they were right big.</i>

41:23.566 --> 41:24.900
(IMITATING EXPLOSION)

41:30.322 --> 41:34.076
<i>Within a few years they had
turned $110,000 into $30 million.</i>

41:34.160 --> 41:35.880
<i>But then it was time
to go to New York City.</i>

41:35.911 --> 41:38.539
<i>And so far, it wasn't going very well.</i>

41:38.622 --> 41:40.374
So what if it does seem interesting. No...

41:40.457 --> 41:43.961
No bank will give us our ISDA.
We're dead in the water.

41:45.462 --> 41:47.882
These kind of trades
are totally out of the question.

41:47.965 --> 41:49.592
We got to call Ben.

41:50.718 --> 41:51.719
(EXHALES)

41:51.802 --> 41:53.304
Let's call Ben!

41:54.180 --> 41:56.265
JARED: <i>Ben Rickert was
a former trader in Singapore</i>

41:56.348 --> 41:59.101
